lzh_formatted:
  title: 三田渡
  author: 朴誾
  language: lzh
  text: 百尺先爭廣津風。一霎相催夢村雨。我行無日不風波。今日又如昨日苦。巨浪如屋倐如山。誰遣長鯨恣呼吸。未上分寸落尋尺。有似魚躍龍門級。操舟若神黃帽郞。獨立沿洄騁千巧。亦如壯士挽強弩。氣力欲盡猶稍稍。三田渡口聊繫蓬。擧眼華山對親故。雲霧蓬勃東南陲。塵沙澒洞牛馬路。齋心血面牋天翁。寧不爲我借一便。末勢蕭蕭暫拗怒。散漫微瀾蹙輕練。移舟欵欵趁落日。互歌軋軋驚水府。蒼茫烟樹楮子島。掩苒漁村豆毛浦。長年三老且緩棹。瓦盆濁酒要勸汝。對余一笑言不忤。唯有愚民容齟齬。依依月色墮巾袂。湛湛空明鑑毛髮。西邊長星太爛熳。飛過驚烏何倉卒。狎鷗下纜欲三更。鳴艫更侵鷄犬曉。黃鸝惱人忽數聲。短短長長楊柳杪。天公餉我故多事。風雨不惡晴亦可。已向湖山飽絶勝。遮莫平生饒坎軻。
korean:
  title: 광나루[廣津]에서 풍우가 심하기에 애써 저어 삼전도
  author: 박은
  language: kor
  text: |-
    광나루서 백 자 바람과 싸우고 나서
    몽촌서 한 보지락 비를 만났네
    내 길에 풍파가 없는 날이 없으니
    오늘이 또 어제같이 괴롭기만 하구나
    큰 물결이 집채만큼 금시 산만큼
    누가 보낸 큰 고래가 물을 뿜어대는고
    한 치도 못 올라서 몇 길, 몇 자 떨어지니
    마치 고기가 용문 층계를 뛰어오르듯
    귀신처럼 배 다루는 저 뱃사공은
    혼자 서서 감돌며 온갖 재주 부리네
    또한 장사가 굳센 활을 당기듯이
    기운이 거의 다하다가도 또 조금씩, 조금씩
    삼전도 어귀에서 그나마 배를 매니
    바라뵈는 삼각산이 친구를 대한 듯
    동남 저쪽에 운무가 자욱하고
    먼지가 뽀얗게 이는 마소들의 길
    재심ㆍ혈면하고 하느님께 올리는 말씀
    “내게 왜 일편풍을 안 빌려 주나이까”
    물결이 차차 갈앉아 잠시 성냄[怒] 눙치니
    잔물결 찰싹찰싹 뱃전을 걷어차네
    해질녘에 어여차 배를 옮겨 가니
    “이어라, 이어라” 뱃노래가 수궁을 놀래누나
    아득한 연수는 저게 뚝섬이로고
    뽀얀 어촌 저기가 바로 두모개
    “늙은 뱃사공아, 잠시 배를 늦추어라
    질동이의 막걸리를 너한테 권하련다”
    그가 나를 보고 웃고 받아 마시니
    우민만이 구차한 것을 탓하지 않누나
    부드러운 달빛이 의건에 떨어지고
    해맑은 물빛이 머리칼까지 비추는데
    서쪽에 낯선 별이 너무도 반짝이니
    날아가는 놀란 까마귀 부산도 한지고
    압구 밑에 닻 내리니 거의 삼경인데
    닭 울 녘에 다시 노젓는 소리
    꾀꼬리가 사람 녹여 꾀꼴꾀꼴 두어 소리
    촐랑촐랑, 치렁치렁, 버들가지 춤추누나
    하늘이 내게 낸 턱 짐짓 다사했다마는
    풍우도 괜찮았고 개어서 좋았네
    내 이미 호산에서 절승에 물렸거니
    그까짓 평생의 불우쯤이야 심하다 탓하리오
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1410_010_0600&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: 'At Samjeon Ferry: A Boat Journey Through Storm and Rain'
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At Gwangnaeru we fought the wind for a hundred feet,
    then met the rain at Mongchon—a mere breath of it.
    Every day of my travels brings wind and waves,
    and today proves no gentler than yesterday's torment.

    The great swells tower like houses, shift like mountains,
    and who has sent this great whale to spout and breathe?
    We cannot rise an inch before sliding several fathoms,
    like a carp leaping toward the Dragon Gate's steep ascent.

    That oarsman works like a spirit possessed,
    standing alone, steering in spirals, conjuring endless tricks—
    like a strong warrior drawing his bow to its limit,
    straining past exhaustion, yet still pushing forward, bit by bit.

    At the mouth of Samjeon Ferry we finally tie up,
    and I gaze upon Samgak Mountain like greeting an old friend.
    Clouds and mist billow toward the southeast,
    dust rising white where cattle and horses tread.
    With purified heart and blood-marked face, I address Heaven:
    "Why do you not lend me a favorable wind?"

    The waves subside, growing calm and almost tame,
    small ripples lapping gently at the bow.
    We move the boat leisurely toward the setting sun,
    while boatmen's chants—rhythmic and sharp—startle the dragon palace.

    Through hazy trees I glimpse Ttuk Island,
    and beyond, the fishing village of Dumogae.
    An old oarsman says: "Let me slow the boat,
    and I'll offer you turbid rice wine from a cracked bowl."
    He smiles at me, accepts, and drinks without complaint—
    only the foolish find fault with such simple courtesy.

    Gentle moonlight falls upon my sleeve,
    clear water mirrors every strand of hair.
    A strange star shines too bright in the west,
    and startled crows fly past in haste.
    Beneath Apgu we drop anchor near the third watch,
    and oars sound again as dawn approaches—
    warblers sing their sweet lament, crying out in pairs,
    their trilling, swaying willow branches in the breeze.

    Heaven has filled my life with manifold concerns,
    yet wind and rain brought no true hardship, fair weather its gift.
    I have already gorged myself on the lake's transcendent beauty,
    so why lament a lifetime's common sorrows?
  footnotes:
    - Gwangnaeru (광나루) and Samjeon Ferry (삼전도) are landmarks on the Han River near Seoul, historically significant locations.
    - Mongchon refers to a location associated with the ancient Baekje kingdom, adding historical resonance to the journey.
    - The Dragon Gate (용문) is a classical reference from Chinese legend, symbolizing difficult ascent and transformation.
    - Samgak Mountain is a peak near Seoul, visible from the Han River; the poem's apostrophe to it suggests communion between traveler and landscape.
    - The final stanza expresses a Daoist or Buddhist acceptance of life's hardships through communion with nature.
